class Cond:
    """
    The :class:`GLib.Cond` struct is an opaque data structure that represents a
    condition. Threads can block on a :class:`GLib.Cond` if they find a certain
    condition to be false. If other threads change the state of this
    condition they signal the :class:`GLib.Cond`, and that causes the waiting
    threads to be woken up.

    Consider the following example of a shared variable.  One or more
    threads can wait for data to be published to the variable and when
    another thread publishes the data, it can signal one of the waiting
    threads to wake up to collect the data.

    Here is an example for using :class:`GLib.Cond` to block a thread until a condition
    is satisfied:
    |[<!-- language="C" -->
      gpointer current_data = NULL;
      :class:`GLib.Mutex` data_mutex;
      :class:`GLib.Cond` data_cond;

      void
      push_data (gpointer data)
      {
        :meth:`GLib.Mutex.lock` (&data_mutex);
        current_data = data;
        :meth:`GLib.Cond.signal` (&data_cond);
        :meth:`GLib.Mutex.unlock` (&data_mutex);
      }

      gpointer
      pop_data (void)
      {
        gpointer data;

        :meth:`GLib.Mutex.lock` (&data_mutex);
        while (!current_data)
          :meth:`GLib.Cond.wait` (&data_cond, &data_mutex);
        data = current_data;
        current_data = NULL;
        :meth:`GLib.Mutex.unlock` (&data_mutex);

        return data;
      }
    ]|
    Whenever a thread calls pop_data() now, it will wait until
    current_data is non-``None``, i.e. until some other thread
    has called push_data().

    The example shows that use of a condition variable must always be
    paired with a mutex.  Without the use of a mutex, there would be a
    race between the check of ``current_data`` by the while loop in
    pop_data() and waiting. Specifically, another thread could set
    ``current_data`` after the check, and signal the cond (with nobody
    waiting on it) before the first thread goes to sleep. :class:`GLib.Cond` is
    specifically useful for its ability to release the mutex and go
    to sleep atomically.

    It is also important to use the :meth:`GLib.Cond.wait` and :meth:`GLib.Cond.wait_until`
    functions only inside a loop which checks for the condition to be
    true.  See :meth:`GLib.Cond.wait` for an explanation of why the condition may
    not be true even after it returns.

    If a :class:`GLib.Cond` is allocated in static storage then it can be used
    without initialisation.  Otherwise, you should call :meth:`GLib.Cond.init`
    on it and :meth:`GLib.Cond.clear` when done.

    A :class:`GLib.Cond` should only be accessed via the g_cond_ functions.
    """
    gimeta: ClassVar[_GIMeta]
    p: int
    i: list[int]
    def broadcast(self) -> None:
        """
        If threads are waiting for ``cond``, all of them are unblocked.
        If no threads are waiting for ``cond``, this function has no effect.
        It is good practice to lock the same mutex as the waiting threads
        while calling this function, though not required.
        """
    def clear(self) -> None:
        """
        Frees the resources allocated to a :class:`GLib.Cond` with :meth:`GLib.Cond.init`.

        This function should not be used with a :class:`GLib.Cond` that has been
        statically allocated.

        Calling :meth:`GLib.Cond.clear` for a :class:`GLib.Cond` on which threads are
        blocking leads to undefined behaviour.
        """
    def init(self) -> None:
        """
        Initialises a :class:`GLib.Cond` so that it can be used.

        This function is useful to initialise a :class:`GLib.Cond` that has been
        allocated as part of a larger structure.  It is not necessary to
        initialise a :class:`GLib.Cond` that has been statically allocated.

        To undo the effect of :meth:`GLib.Cond.init` when a :class:`GLib.Cond` is no longer
        needed, use :meth:`GLib.Cond.clear`.

        Calling :meth:`GLib.Cond.init` on an already-initialised :class:`GLib.Cond` leads
        to undefined behaviour.
        """
    def signal(self) -> None:
        """
        If threads are waiting for ``cond``, at least one of them is unblocked.
        If no threads are waiting for ``cond``, this function has no effect.
        It is good practice to hold the same lock as the waiting thread
        while calling this function, though not required.
        """
    def wait(self, mutex: Mutex) -> None:
        """
        Atomically releases ``mutex`` and waits until ``cond`` is signalled.
        When this function returns, ``mutex`` is locked again and owned by the
        calling thread.

        When using condition variables, it is possible that a spurious wakeup
        may occur (ie: :meth:`GLib.Cond.wait` returns even though :meth:`GLib.Cond.signal` was
        not called).  It's also possible that a stolen wakeup may occur.
        This is when :meth:`GLib.Cond.signal` is called, but another thread acquires
        ``mutex`` before this thread and modifies the state of the program in
        such a way that when :meth:`GLib.Cond.wait` is able to return, the expected
        condition is no longer met.

        For this reason, :meth:`GLib.Cond.wait` must always be used in a loop.  See
        the documentation for :class:`GLib.Cond` for a complete example.
        """
    def wait_until(self, mutex: Mutex, end_time: int) -> bool:
